<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <title>BAA or Not?</title>
  <style>
    * { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }
    body {
      font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, sans-serif;
      line-height: 1.6;
      color: #1e293b;
      background: #f8fafc;
      padding: 2rem;
      max-width: 640px;
      margin: 0 auto;
    }
    h1 { font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    h2 { font-size: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    p { margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .disclaimer {
      background: #fef3c7;
      border: 1px solid #f59e0b;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      font-size: 0.875rem;
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
    .question {
      background: #fff;
      border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 1rem;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
    }
    .question label { display: block; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .radio-group { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; }
    .radio-group label { font-weight: normal; }
    button {
      background: #2563eb;
      color: #fff;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem;
      font-size: 1rem;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
    button:hover { background: #1d4ed8; }
    .result {
      background: #fff;
      border: 2px solid #2563eb;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 1.5rem;
      margin-top: 1rem;
    }
    .result.required { border-color: #dc2626; }
    .result.not-required { border-color: #16a34a; }
    footer {
      margin-top: 2rem;
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      color: #94a3b8;
      text-align: center;
    }
    a { color: #2563eb; }
    .definitions { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .definitions h2 { font-size: 1.125rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    details {
      background: #fff;
      border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    details summary {
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      cursor: pointer;
      font-weight: 600;
      font-size: 0.9375rem;
    }
    details summary:hover { background: #f1f5f9; border-radius: 0.5rem; }
    details[open] summary { border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0; }
    details .detail-body {
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      font-size: 0.875rem;
      line-height: 1.7;
    }
    details .detail-body p { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    details .detail-body .source {
      font-size: 0.8125rem;
      color: #64748b;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>BAA or Not?</h1>
  <p>Determine whether you need a Business Associate Agreement under HIPAA.</p>
  <div class="disclaimer">
    <strong>For entertainment and educational purposes only.</strong>
    This tool does not provide legal advice. Consult qualified counsel
    for binding determinations.
  </div>
  <div class="definitions">
    <h2>Key definitions</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>Covered Entity &mdash; a health plan, clearinghouse, or provider subject to HIPAA</summary>
      <div class="detail-body">
        <p>
          A covered entity is a health plan, health care clearinghouse, or health
          care provider that transmits any health information electronically in
          connection with a HIPAA-covered transaction. The three categories are:
          health plans (including health insurers, HMOs, and government programs
          such as Medicare and Medicaid), health care clearinghouses (entities that
          process nonstandard health information into standard formats), and health
          care providers who conduct certain electronic transactions such as claims
          or benefit eligibility inquiries. An entity that does not fall into one
          of these categories is not a covered entity and is not directly subject
          to HIPAA.
        </p>
        <p class="source">
          Source:
          <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/covered-entities/index.html"
             rel="noopener">HHS &mdash; Covered Entities</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Business Associate &mdash; a person or organization handling PHI on behalf of a covered entity</summary>
      <div class="detail-body">
        <p>
          A business associate is a person or organization that performs functions
          or activities involving the use or disclosure of protected health
          information on behalf of, or provides services to, a covered entity.
          Examples include claims processing, data analysis, billing, legal,
          actuarial, accounting, and consulting services where access to PHI is
          necessary. The HITECH Act and the 2013 Omnibus Rule made business
          associates directly liable for compliance with certain HIPAA Privacy
          and Security Rule provisions. A covered entity must obtain satisfactory
          assurances through a written Business Associate Agreement that the
          business associate will appropriately safeguard PHI.
        </p>
        <p class="source">
          Source:
          <a href="https://www.hhs.gov/hipaa/for-professionals/privacy/guidance/business-associates/index.html"
             rel="noopener">HHS &mdash; Business Associates</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Protected Health Information (PHI) &mdash; individually identifiable health information held by a covered entity</summary>
      <div class="detail-body">
        <p>
          PHI is individually identifiable health information transmitted or
          maintained in any form or medium by a covered entity or its business
          associate. It includes health information (including demographic data)
          that relates to the past, present, or future physical or mental health
          condition of an individual, the provision of health care, or payment for
          health care, and that identifies the individual or could reasonably be
          used to identify the individual. PHI encompasses information in any
          form&mdash;electronic, paper, or oral. The definition specifically
          excludes education records covered by FERPA and employment records held
          by a covered entity in its role as employer.
        </p>
        <p class="source">
          Source:
          <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/45/section-160.103"
             rel="noopener">45 CFR &sect; 160.103</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Personally Identifiable Information (PII) &mdash; any data that can distinguish or trace an individual's identity</summary>
      <div class="detail-body">
        <p>
          PII is any information maintained by an agency that can be used to
          distinguish or trace an individual's identity, either alone or when
          combined with other information linked or linkable to a specific
          individual. Examples include name, Social Security number, biometric
          records, date and place of birth, and similar data. NIST distinguishes
          between &ldquo;linked&rdquo; information (directly tied to an
          individual, such as an SSN) and &ldquo;linkable&rdquo; information
          (which could be combined with other data to identify someone, such as
          date of birth plus zip code). PII is a broader concept than PHI and
          is not specific to HIPAA, but overlap is significant: most PHI is
          also PII.
        </p>
        <p class="source">
          Source:
          <a href="https://csrc.nist.gov/pubs/sp/800/122/final"
             rel="noopener">NIST SP 800-122</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
  <%= yield %>
  <footer>
    <%= BaaOrNot::REVISION || "dev" %>
  </footer>
</body>
</html>
